d violence in the region. Through them she learned that a fair amount of petty, small-scale illicit trading goes unreported—a consequence of a community invested in promoting the idea that the border is a secure place that does not warrant militarized attention. The author's work demonstrates that while media is often seen as a powerful tool for spreading a sense of danger and uncertainty, sensationalizing crime and violence, and creating moral panics, journalists can actually do the opposite. Those who selectively report on illegal activities use the news to tell particular types of stories in an attempt to make their communities look and ultimately be more secure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBorder securityxTri-Border Area (Argentina, Brazil, and Paraguay)xSouth AmericaxTri-Border Area. 0aBorder securityzTri-Border Area (Argentina, Brazil, and Paraguay). 0aCrimexPress coveragexTri-Border Area (Argentina, Brazil, and Paraguay). 0aCrimexPress coveragezTri-Border Area (Argentina, Brazil, and Paraguay). 0aCrimexTri-Border Area (Argentina, Brazil, and Paraguay). 0aCrimezTri-Border Area (Argentina, Brazil, and Paraguay). 0aSecurity, InternationalxTri-Border Area (Argentina, Brazil, and Paraguay). 0aSecurity, InternationalzTri-Border Area (Argentina, Brazil, and Paraguay). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095937840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959378423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959378/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles